# Day 29 - OSPF Part 2

## OSPF Metric

OSPF uses a metric called cost.

The route with the lowest total cost is preferred.

OSPF cost is based on interface bandwidth.

Formula:

Cost = Reference Bandwidth / Interface Bandwidth

By default, the reference bandwidth is 100 Mbps.

This creates a problem because:
- Ethernet 10 Mbps = cost 10
- FastEthernet 100 Mbps = cost 1
- GigabitEthernet 1000 Mbps = cost 1
- 10 GigabitEthernet 10000 Mbps = cost 1

So by default, FastEthernet, GigabitEthernet, and 10Gig Ethernet can all end up with the same cost of 1.

That is why the default reference bandwidth is not good enough in modern networks.

To fix this, it is recommended to change the reference bandwidth on every router in the OSPF domain.

Command:
- `auto-cost reference-bandwidth <value>`

Important:
- The value is entered in Mbps
- It must be the same on all OSPF routers

Example:
- `auto-cost reference-bandwidth 100000`

That means:
- FastEthernet 100 Mbps = 100000 / 100 = 1000
- GigabitEthernet 1000 Mbps = 100000 / 1000 = 100
- 10Gig Ethernet 10000 Mbps = 100000 / 10000 = 10

This gives a much better path selection.

## Route Cost

The total OSPF cost to a destination is the sum of the outgoing interface costs along the path.

Example:
If a packet goes from R1 to R2 and then to R4, and each outgoing interface has a cost of 100, the total route cost is:

- 100 + 100 + 100 = 300

Loopback interfaces have a cost of 1.

So if R1 reaches a loopback on R2, the path cost includes:
- R1 outgoing interface cost
- plus loopback cost 1

Example:
- 100 + 1 = 101

## Ways to Change OSPF Cost

There are three ways to influence OSPF cost.

### 1. Change the reference bandwidth
This is the recommended method.

Command:
- `auto-cost reference-bandwidth <value>`

### 2. Manually set the cost on an interface
This overrides the automatic calculation.

Command:
- `ip ospf cost <value>`

Example:
- `ip ospf cost 10000`

### 3. Change the bandwidth value on the interface
This is not recommended.

Command:
- `bandwidth <value>`

Important:
- This command changes the bandwidth value used for calculations
- It does not change the actual physical speed of the interface
- The real interface speed is changed with the `speed` command, not the `bandwidth` command

Also note:
- `bandwidth` is configured in kilobits per second
- `auto-cost reference-bandwidth` is configured in megabits per second

So always pay attention to units.

## Useful Show Commands for Cost

To check OSPF cost on a specific interface:
- `show ip ospf interface <interface>`

To quickly check all OSPF-enabled interfaces:
- `show ip ospf interface brief`

## OSPF Neighbors

OSPF works only if routers become neighbors.

This is one of the most important parts of OSPF.

If routers do not become neighbors:
- they do not exchange LSAs
- they do not build the same LSDB
- they do not calculate routes correctly
- OSPF will not work

When OSPF is activated on an interface, the router starts sending Hello packets.

These Hello packets are used to:
- discover potential neighbors
- check compatibility
- build the neighbor relationship

### Hello Packet Facts
- Default Hello timer on Ethernet = 10 seconds
- Default Dead timer on Ethernet = 40 seconds
- Hello packets are sent to multicast address `224.0.0.5`
- OSPF uses IP protocol number `89`

Important:
- RIP multicast = 224.0.0.9
- EIGRP multicast = 224.0.0.10
- OSPF multicast = 224.0.0.5

## OSPF Neighbor States

Routers go through a series of states before reaching a full adjacency.

The correct order is:

- Down
- Init
- 2-Way
- Exstart
- Exchange
- Loading
- Full

You need to know this order.

### Down
The router does not know the neighbor yet.

It may be sending Hello packets, but it has not received one from the other router.

### Init
The router received a Hello packet from the neighbor.

However, its own Router ID is not yet listed in that Hello packet.

So communication is only one-way at this moment.

### 2-Way
Each router has received a Hello packet that contains its own Router ID.

This means two-way communication is working.

At this point:
- routers are neighbors
- they are ready to move forward

On some network types, the DR and BDR election happens here.

### Exstart
The routers decide which one will be Master and which one will be Slave.

The router with the higher Router ID becomes the Master.

This is only for the database exchange process.

They use DBD packets to negotiate this.

### Exchange
The routers exchange DBD packets.

These packets contain summaries of the LSAs in each router’s LSDB.

They are not sending full LSAs yet.

They are only describing what they have.

### Loading
The routers compare what they have learned from the DBD exchange.

If a router is missing LSAs, it sends LSR packets to request them.

The other router replies with LSU packets.

Then LSAck packets are used to acknowledge receipt.

### Full
The routers now have a full adjacency.

Their LSDBs are synchronized.

OSPF is fully operational between them.

After that, they continue sending Hellos to keep the adjacency alive.

## OSPF Packet Types

There are five main OSPF packet types.

### 1. Hello
Used to discover and maintain neighbors.

### 2. DBD (Database Description)
Used to describe the LSDB contents.

### 3. LSR (Link State Request)
Used to request missing LSAs.

### 4. LSU (Link State Update)
Used to send LSAs.

### 5. LSAck (Link State Acknowledgment)
Used to acknowledge received LSAs.

## Neighbor Maintenance

Even after Full state is reached, routers continue sending Hellos.

This keeps the adjacency alive.

The Dead timer resets every time a Hello is received.

If the Dead timer reaches 0:
- the neighbor is declared down
- the neighbor entry is removed
- OSPF recalculates if needed

## OSPF Show Commands for Neighbors

To check OSPF neighbors:
- `show ip ospf neighbor`

Useful things you can see:
- Neighbor Router ID
- State
- Dead timer
- DR / BDR role

To check detailed OSPF interface info:
- `show ip ospf interface`

Useful things you can see:
- Hello timer
- Dead timer
- Cost
- Neighbor count
- Adjacent neighbor count

## Additional OSPF Configuration

### Enable OSPF directly on an interface
Instead of using the network command, you can activate OSPF directly under the interface.

Command:
- `ip ospf <process-id> area <area-id>`

Example:
- `ip ospf 1 area 0`

This is done in interface configuration mode.

### Passive Interface
You can make a specific interface passive with:
- `passive-interface <interface>`

You can also make all interfaces passive by default:
- `passive-interface default`

Then re-enable only the ones that should form neighbors:
- `no passive-interface <interface>`

This can be useful when you have many passive interfaces.

If OSPF is configured directly on interfaces instead of with network commands, `show ip protocols` will display:
- `routing on interfaces configured explicitly`

instead of listing routing networks.

